  "prompt": "What are time zones?",
  "response": "Time zones are regions of the Earth that have the same standard time. They were established to allow people in different areas to coordinate activities and schedules, based on the position of the sun in the sky, which affects the amount of natural daylight. The concept simplifies global timekeeping by dividing the world into roughly 24 longitudinal zones, each approximately 15 degrees of longitude apart.\n\nEach time zone is typically one hour ahead or behind its neighboring time zones. The reference point for time zones is the Prime Meridian (0\u00b0 longitude), which runs through Greenwich, London; this is known as Greenwich Mean Time (GMT) or Coordinated Universal Time (UTC). As a result, time zones are often designated as being a number of hours ahead of or behind UTC, such as UTC-5 or UTC+2.\n\nSome regions adjust their clocks seasonally for daylight saving time (DST), which shifts the local time, usually by one hour, to make better use of daylight during the longer days of summer.\n\nTime zones accommodate geographical and political boundaries, meaning some countries might have multiple time zones, and some time zones don't strictly adhere to the 15-degree width or hourly difference.",
